<html><head><meta name="color-scheme" content="light dark"><meta charset="utf-8"></head><body><pre>{"id":1632,"date":"2024-12-15T23:55:00","date_gmt":"2024-12-15T12:55:00","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/?p=1632"},"modified":"2025-09-27T14:24:11","modified_gmt":"2025-09-27T04:24:11","slug":"lessons-for-educators-from-aeu-elections-organise-and-strike","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/lessons-for-educators-from-aeu-elections-organise-and-strike\/","title":{"rendered":"Lessons for Educators from AEU Elections: Organise and Strike!"},"content":{"rendered":"\n&lt;p&gt;The results of the recent Australian Education Union (AEU) internal elections in Victoria give us educators one clear lesson \u2013 the time to organise for a strike is now!&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;Socialists and other activists challenged the existing AEU bureaucracy for several paid leadership positions in the most recent elections. Comparing the results for Branch President with those for the last time there was a competitive election (2018) shows some stark changes.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;Member participation jumped from a dismal 16% to (a less dismal) 28% showing an increased interest and participation from the rank and file. The ticket challenging the existing leadership \u2013 Fight the Crisis \u2013 mustered up a vote of 35% compared to only 21% when a similar challenge was lodged in 2018.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;The lesson from these results is that the membership base is now more active, more willing to participate, and more willing to vote for an alternative to the status quo. Our job is to ensure that the willingness to vote gets transferred to a willingness to organise and take action. By organising together we must convince active members that power doesn\u2019t lie in elections and leaders, but in the rank and file.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;In the upcoming agreement beginning in 2026, teachers and education support staff need a significant pay increase, improved conditions and, importantly, improved dignity in the workplace. This doesn\u2019t even cover the crisis of underfunding of schools that draconian industrial relations laws ban us taking action over. To achieve what we deserve, we must strike.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;Strikes do not &lt;em&gt;just happen&lt;\/em&gt;. They are &lt;em&gt;organised&lt;\/em&gt;. The argument for industrial action is clear \u2013 it is the only way we will win the pay and conditions we deserve. But a strike consisting of only 28% of the workforce will not be effective.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;While there is a growing number of educators wanting to fight the status quo, the majority do not see the value in engaging with union democracy. Our message to non-members, disengaged members, and active members is consistent \u2013 if we want change, we must organise it ourselves.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;We need to have regular 1:1 organising conversations with non-members to convince them to join the union to vote on industrial action. We need to have 1:1 organising conversations with members to convince them a strike is necessary. Our colleagues need to know the power is in our hands and we\u2019re all essential to the future of our industry. They\u2019re receptive to ideas of a major strike, but we need to engage them by organising for a log of claims (our demands) that are worth fighting for.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;The road to a historic teacher\u2019s agreement must include a significant strike. But the first steps will always be organising our co-workers. If you want to know more about these conversations and link up with fellow educators check out &lt;a href=\"https:\/\/schoolworkbulletin.au\/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https:\/\/schoolworkbulletin.au\/\"&gt;our website&lt;\/a&gt; or contact us.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n&lt;div class=\"wp-block-image\"&gt;\n&lt;figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"&gt;&lt;img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"1024\" src=\"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-content\/uploads\/2024\/12\/possible-secondary-image-1024x1024.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1635\" style=\"width:317px;height:auto\" srcset=\"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-content\/uploads\/2024\/12\/possible-secondary-image-1024x1024.png 1024w, https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-content\/uploads\/2024\/12\/possible-secondary-image-300x300.png 300w, https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-content\/uploads\/2024\/12\/possible-secondary-image-150x150.png 150w, https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-content\/uploads\/2024\/12\/possible-secondary-image-768x768.png 768w, https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-content\/uploads\/2024\/12\/possible-secondary-image.png 1067w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/&gt;&lt;\/figure&gt;\n&lt;\/div&gt;","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"The results of the recent AEU internal elections in Victoria give us educators one clear lesson \u2013 the time to organise for a strike is now!\n&lt;a class=\"moretag\" href=\"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/lessons-for-educators-from-aeu-elections-organise-and-strike\/\"&gt; [...]&lt;\/a&gt;","protected":false},"author":11,"featured_media":1867,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"_coblocks_attr":"","_coblocks_dimensions":"","_coblocks_responsive_height":"","_coblocks_accordion_ie_support":"","footnotes":""},"categories":[2,28],"tags":[59,73,72,46],"class_list":["post-1632","post","type-post","status-publish","format-standard","has-post-thumbnail","hentry","category-anvil","category-workers","tag-aeu","tag-industrial-action","tag-strike","tag-unions"],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/1632","targetHints":{"allow":["GET"]}}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/11"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=1632"}],"version-history":[{"count":4,"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/1632\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":1724,"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/1632\/revisions\/1724"}],"wp:featuredmedia":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media\/1867"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=1632"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=1632"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/tags?post=1632"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}</pre><div class="json-formatter-container"></div></body></html>